SIMPLE: stretcher
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stretcher
<hw>Stretch"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One
who, or that which, stretches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Masonry)</fld> <def>A brick or stone laid with its
longer dimension in the line of direction of the wall.</def>
<rj><au>Gwilt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A piece of timber used in
building.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A narrow crosspiece
of the bottom of a boat against which a rower braces his feet.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A crosspiece placed between the sides of a boat to
keep them apart when hoisted up and griped.</def>
<rj><au>Dana.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A litter, or frame, for carrying disabled, wounded,
or dead persons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An overstretching of the truth; a lie.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>One of the rods in an umbrella, attached at one end
to one of the ribs, and at the other to the tube sliding upon the
handle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>An instrument for stretching boots or
gloves.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>The frame upon which canvas is stretched for a
painting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stretching</ent>⟦br⟧
